[normal]Opportunities and b[bold]arriers[bold] facing the uptak[bold]e of low carbon heating in [bold]UK homes[bold]&#xa0;[bold]1.1
[normal] 
[normal]HHIC and HWA 
[normal]support
[normal] 
[normal]the need to 
[normal]reduce carbon emissions in order to 
[normal]help 
[normal]combat climate change and to establish longer term energy 
[normal]security
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]At the same time we recognise the 
[normal]ongoing 
[normal]need 
[normal]to provide affordable an
[normal]d effec
[normal]tive heating for UK households along
[normal] with the implications and needs to alleviate fuel poverty
[normal].
[normal]1.2
[normal] 
[normal]Reducing the amoun
[normal]t of carbon used for heating 
[normal]UK homes is a significant 
[normal]challenge and 
[normal]progress has been relatively slow. There are a number
[normal] of
[normal] factors which 
[normal]are 
[normal]li
[normal]mit
[normal]i
[normal]ng
[normal] the pace of decarbonisation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3
[normal] 
[normal]Faced with all of these issues it would be easy 
[normal]to focus the decarbonisation agenda 
[normal]on other market sectors. Heating and hot
[normal] water 
[normal]are together
[normal] responsible for 
[normal]over 80 % of the domestic sectors energy consumption
[normal] and
[normal] 27%
[normal] of
[normal] the UK’s
[normal] carbon emissions and so cannot be ignored 
[normal]if 
[normal]the 2030 and 2050 
[normal]ambitions
[normal] are to be achieved.
[normal]1.4
[normal] 
[normal]The inquiry ra
[normal]ises a number of 
[normal]critic
[normal]al questions about the opportunities and challenges to reduce carbon emissions from domestic heating. HHIC has prod
[normal]uced a report entitled Pathways 
[normal]to Domestic Heating which provides some new and alternative options to reduce the carb
[normal]on intensity of domestic heating and in doing so addresses a number of questions raised in the Inquiry.
[normal]&#xa0;
